BEGIN_PGML
[$p] is an architect and [$p->they] [$p->are] making a scale model of a building. The actual building will be [`[$building]`] ft tall. In the model, the height of the building will be [`[$model]`] in tall and there will be a little model person standing next to the building. How tall should [$p] make the model of that person who is meant to represent a [`5`] ft [`6`] in tall person?

[_]{$answer}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Let [`h`] be the height of the person in [$p]'s model, which we'll measure in inches. We'll create a proportional equation that compares the building and person's heights in the model to their heights in real life:

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\text{height of model building in inches}}{\text{height of actual building in feet}}\amp=\frac{\text{height of model person in inches}}{\text{height of actual person in feet}}\\
\frac{[$model]\,\text{in}}{[$building]\,\text{ft}}\amp=\frac{h\,\text{in}}{5\,\text{ft}\,6\text{in}}
\end{aligned}
```]

Before we can just eliminate the units, we'll need to convert 5 ft[$NBSP]*6 in to feet:

[```
                \frac{2\,\text{in}}{30\,\text{ft}}=\frac{h\,\text{in}}{5.5\,\text{ft}}
              ```]

Now we can remove the units and continue solving:

[```\newcommand{\multiplyright}[2][\cdot]{{\highlight{{{}#1#2}}}}\newcommand{\multiplyleft}[2][\cdot]{{\highlight{{#2#1{}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{[$model]}{[$building]}\amp=\frac{h}{5.5}\\
\multiplyleft{[$building]\cdot5.5}\frac{[$model]}{[$building]}\amp=\frac{h}{5.5}\multiplyright{[$building]\cdot5.5}\\
5.5\cdot [$model] \amp= [$building]h\\
[$aux[0]] \amp= [$building]h\\
h\amp\approx [$ans]
\end{aligned}
```]

[$p] should make the model be [`[$answer]`] tall.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

